# Writers Room — feedback log

This file is the long-term editorial memory for your project. It is **read by the Coordinator
at the start of every run** and **appended to at the end** with the user's review.

The Coordinator does NOT auto-apply entries as hard rules. It propagates them as soft
preferences to the relevant sub-agents (Writer, Style, Plan, Linking).

When a similar entry appears 3+ times, you should **manually promote** it to a hard rule in
`config.yml` (e.g. add a phrase to `style.banned_phrases`, a synonym to
`style.preferred_lexicon`, shorten `length.max_paragraph_words`, etc.). This separation between
dynamic feedback and static rules is what makes the skill durably learn without silently
mutating your editorial config.

Each entry should be dated, anchor a specific article, and stay short. The Coordinator can
ingest plain prose — there is no schema. The fictional examples below show useful patterns;
delete them before using the file in production.

---

## 2025-01-15 — Article: "How modern teams ship documentation alongside code"

**Liked**
- The thesis "documentation is a deployment artifact, not an afterthought" was the right hook.
- Each section opened with its key idea — the inverted pyramid is being respected.
- External sources were diverse (no two links pointed to the same domain).

**Change next time**
- The opening paragraph leaned on the rhetorical pattern "X is no longer Y, it is Z".
  This pattern has shown up in several recent drafts. Vary the opener.
- Consider adding a short "what this article does NOT cover" paragraph so readers
  with adjacent intents (API reference docs, onboarding guides) self-disqualify quickly.

**Stop**
- Avoid the transition word "concretely" at the start of paragraphs. Already counted twice
  in the last three articles. If it appears again, promote to `style.banned_phrases`.

